{"title_page": "\u2018\u014cma\u2019o", "text_new": "{{Speciesbox\n| status = VU\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=IUCN>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22708579/0 |title=''Myadestes obscurus'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=26 November 2013}}</ref>\n| image              = Oma'o (9-4-2017) Pu'u O'o trail, Kipuka Ainahou section, Hawai'i co, Hawaii -04jpg (37545163396).jpg\n| genus              = Myadestes\n| species            = obscurus\n| authority          = ([[Johann Friedrich Gmelin|J. F. Gmelin]], 1789)\n}}\n\n{{More citations needed|article|date=January 2009}}\n\nThe '''\u02bb\u014dma\u02bbo''' (''Myadestes obscurus'', also called the '''Hawaiian thrush''') is an [[endemism in birds|endemic]] species of robin-like bird found only on the island of [[Hawaii (island)|Hawaii]]. \u2018\u014cma\u2019o are closely related to the other endemic thrushes of the [[Hawaiian Islands]], the [[k\u0101ma\u02bbo]], the [[oloma\u02bbo]], and the [[puaiohi]]. \u2018\u014cma\u2019o are found primarily in rainforests in the eastern and southeastern regions of the Big Island. Population estimates approximate 170,000 birds, making it the most common of the Hawaiian thrushes. It appears to have a stable population, but because the entire population exists on a small range and is endemic to a single island, it is considered vulnerable.<ref name=IUCN/>\n\n==Description==\n[[File:MyiadestesObscurusSmit.jpg|thumb|left|Illustration by [[Joseph Smit]]]]\nAdult thrushes (males and females are similar in appearance) are mostly nondescript, with a grayish-brown head transitioning to a pale gray below. The back and primaries are a dull olive brown.  They also have whitish vents and undertail coverts.   The juveniles are also similarly dull in coloration, but have pale whitish-buff spotting on the wing coverts.\n\n==Behaviour==\n\u2018\u014cma\u2019os are mostly [[frugivores]], but will take insects or other small invertebrates.\nThe bird has a song that is a set of jerky liquid notes, ''whip-per-weeo-whip-per-weet''. Their many calls include a cat-like rasp, a frog like croak and even a high pitched police whistle type sound. During breeding, the birds make a bulky nest in a tree or [[tree fern]], laying one to three bluish eggs inside.\n\n==Habitat==\nThe \u2018\u014dma\u2019o once lived on most of the land of Hawaii. Today it is restricted to the southern and eastern slopes of the island, mostly above 1,000 meters above sea level, 25 to 30 percent of its ancestral habitat. Its preferred habitat is [[Hawaiian tropical rainforests|rainforest]], but can be found in [[Hawaiian tropical high shrublands|high shrublands]] on [[Mauna Loa]]. Preferred trees include the [[ohia]] and [[koa]].  The Hawaiian thrush avoids areas with [[banana poka]] (an invasive vine). In lower elevations, it appears to be gaining a natural resistance to [[avian malaria]].  Threats to this species include [[habitat destruction]] from housing, tourism development and farming; introduced feral animal predation (mainly rats, cats and mongoose); [[invasive plant]] encroachment; and feral livestock such as goats and pigs.\n\nThe species has been aided by several conservation actions. These include the removal of pigs from several areas in the 1990s, such as [[Hakalau Forest National Wildlife Refuge]], and the control of rats, cats, and ungulates.\n\nThe \u2018\u014dma\u2019o was first described to Western science in 1789 by [[Johann Friedrich Gmelin|Gmelin]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*[http://www.birdlife.org/datazone/species/index.html?action=SpcHTMDetails.asp&sid=6350&m=0 Birdlife Species Factsheet]\n*''Handbook of the Birds of the World Vol 10'',  Josep del Hoyo editor, {{ISBN|84-87334-72-5}}\n\n==External links==\n*ARKive-[https://web.archive.org/web/20080618091814/http://www.arkive.org/species/GES/birds/Myadestes_obscurus/ O'mao images]\n*[http://ibc.lynxeds.com/species/omao-myadestes-obscurus O'mao videos, photos, and sounds] on the Internet Bird Collection\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q3179495}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:'Oma'o}}\n[[Category:Myadestes]]\n[[Category:Birds of Hawaii]]\n[[Category:Endemic fauna of Hawaii]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1789]]\n", "text_old": "{{Speciesbox\n| status = VU\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=IUCN>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22708579/0 |title=''Myadestes obscurus'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=26 November 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| image              = Oma'o (9-4-2017) Pu'u O'o trail, Kipuka Ainahou section, Hawai'i co, Hawaii -04jpg (37545163396).jpg\n| genus              = Myadestes\n| species            = obscurus\n| authority          = ([[Johann Friedrich Gmelin|J. F. Gmelin]], 1789)\n}}\n\n{{More citations needed|article|date=January 2009}}\n\nThe '''\u02bb\u014dma\u02bbo''' (''Myadestes obscurus'', also called the '''Hawaiian thrush''') is an [[endemism in birds|endemic]] species of robin-like bird found only on the island of [[Hawaii (island)|Hawaii]]. \u2018\u014cma\u2019o are closely related to the other endemic thrushes of the [[Hawaiian Islands]], the [[k\u0101ma\u02bbo]], the [[oloma\u02bbo]], and the [[puaiohi]]. \u2018\u014cma\u2019o are found primarily in rainforests in the eastern and southeastern regions of the Big Island. Population estimates approximate 170,000 birds, making it the most common of the Hawaiian thrushes. It appears to have a stable population, but because the entire population exists on a small range and is endemic to a single island, it is considered vulnerable.<ref name=IUCN/>\n\n==Description==\n[[File:MyiadestesObscurusSmit.jpg|thumb|left|Illustration by [[Joseph Smit]]]]\nAdult thrushes (males and females are similar in appearance) are mostly nondescript, with a grayish-brown head transitioning to a pale gray below. The back and primaries are a dull olive brown.  They also have whitish vents and undertail coverts.   The juveniles are also similarly dull in coloration, but have pale whitish-buff spotting on the wing coverts.\n\n==Behaviour==\n\u2018\u014cma\u2019os are mostly [[frugivores]], but will take insects or other small invertebrates.\nThe bird has a song that is a set of jerky liquid notes, ''whip-per-weeo-whip-per-weet''. Their many calls include a cat-like rasp, a frog like croak and even a high pitched police whistle type sound. During breeding, the birds make a bulky nest in a tree or [[tree fern]], laying one to three bluish eggs inside.\n\n==Habitat==\nThe \u2018\u014dma\u2019o once lived on most of the land of Hawaii. Today it is restricted to the southern and eastern slopes of the island, mostly above 1,000 meters above sea level, 25 to 30 percent of its ancestral habitat. Its preferred habitat is [[Hawaiian tropical rainforests|rainforest]], but can be found in [[Hawaiian tropical high shrublands|high shrublands]] on [[Mauna Loa]]. Preferred trees include the [[ohia]] and [[koa]].  The Hawaiian thrush avoids areas with [[banana poka]] (an invasive vine). In lower elevations, it appears to be gaining a natural resistance to [[avian malaria]].  Threats to this species include [[habitat destruction]] from housing, tourism development and farming; introduced feral animal predation (mainly rats, cats and mongoose); [[invasive plant]] encroachment; and feral livestock such as goats and pigs.\n\nThe species has been aided by several conservation actions. These include the removal of pigs from several areas in the 1990s, such as [[Hakalau Forest National Wildlife Refuge]], and the control of rats, cats, and ungulates.\n\nThe \u2018\u014dma\u2019o was first described to Western science in 1789 by [[Johann Friedrich Gmelin|Gmelin]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*[http://www.birdlife.org/datazone/species/index.html?action=SpcHTMDetails.asp&sid=6350&m=0 Birdlife Species Factsheet]\n*''Handbook of the Birds of the World Vol 10'',  Josep del Hoyo editor, {{ISBN|84-87334-72-5}}\n\n==External links==\n*ARKive-[https://web.archive.org/web/20080618091814/http://www.arkive.org/species/GES/birds/Myadestes_obscurus/ O'mao images]\n*[http://ibc.lynxeds.com/species/omao-myadestes-obscurus O'mao videos, photos, and sounds] on the Internet Bird Collection\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q3179495}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:'Oma'o}}\n[[Category:Myadestes]]\n[[Category:Birds of Hawaii]]\n[[Category:Endemic fauna of Hawaii]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1789]]\n", "name_user": "Headbomb", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up, no longer needed, removed: |ref=harv", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%E2%80%98%C5%8Cma%E2%80%99o"}
{"title_page": "Doctor Chakravarty", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Doctor Chakravarthy\n| image          = Doctor_Chakravarty.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| writer         = [[Acharya Atreya]]<br>[[Gollapudi Maruti Rao]] {{small|(dialogues)}}\n| story          = Koduri Kousalya Devi \n| screenplay     = Adurthi Subba Rao\n| producer       = [[D. Madhusudhana Rao]]\n| director       = [[Adurthi Subba Rao]]\n| starring       = [[Akkineni Nageswara Rao]]<br />[[Savitri (actress)|Savitri]]<br />[[Kongara Jaggaiah|Jaggaiah]]<br /> [[Sowcar Janaki]]\n| music          = [[Saluri Rajeswara Rao]]\n| cinematography = P. S. Selvaraj\n| editing        = T. Krishna\n| based on       = ''Chakrabharmanam'' {{small|(Novel)}}\n| studio         = Annapurna Pictures\n| released       = {{Film date|df=y|1964|7|10}}\n| runtime        = 167 mins\n| country        = India\n| language       = Telugu\n| budget         =\n| gross          = \n}}\n\n'''''Doctor Chakravarthy''''' is 1964 [[Telugu cinema|Telugu]] [[drama film]], produced by [[D. Madhusudhana Rao]] under the Annapurna Pictures banner and directed by [[Adurthi Subba Rao]]. It stars [[Akkineni Nageswara Rao]], [[Savitri (actress)|Savitri]],  [[Kongara Jaggaiah|Jaggaiah]] in the lead roles and music composed by [[Saluri Rajeswara Rao]]. The film is based on Koduri Kousalya Devi's  ''Chakrabhramanam'' (Novel). The film was recorded as an ''Industry Hit'' at the box office. It is the first film to win the [[Nandi Award]], instituted by [[Government of Andhra Pradesh]] in 1964. It inspired many people in India to become doctors.<ref>[http://www.chitramala.com/articles/tollywood-4063.html Telugu Articles - Chitramala.com<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100130192602/http://www.chitramala.com/articles/tollywood-4063.html |date=30 January 2010 }}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nDr. Chakravarthy ([[Akkineni Nageswara Rao]]) arrives from abroad and plans to marry his lady love Dr. Sridevi ([[Krishna Kumari (actress)|Krishna Kumari]]). He has an affectionate sister  Sudha ([[Geetanjali (actress)|Geethanjali]]). Chakravarthy is extremely fond of his sister. Sudha is a great musician and loves writing poetry and she marries a loving person. However, by the time Chakravarthy returns to his hometown, his sister is terribly ill and in the last stages of her life. Chakravarthy gets distraught to know that his sister has cancer. Sudha requests Chakravarthy to marry her sister-in-law Nirmala ([[Sowcar Janaki]]) as a dying wish. Chakravarthy doesn't get a chance to tell that he has already loved a woman in life. He suppresses the sadness and marries Nirmala as per his sister's wish. Nirmala is a materialistic person who loves going around for picnics, shopping and doesn't understand the artistic subtleties in life. Chakravarthy is a busy doctor with nonstop work dealing with patients, treatment and tests. He has nothing in common with Nirmala and their life goes on in a mechanical way, despite staying under one roof. The story makes a turn when Chakravarthy meets Ravindra ([[Jaggayya (actor)|Jaggayya]]) and his wife Madhavi ([[Savitri (actress)|Savitri]]). Madhavi is a great veena player and writes poetry exactly like Chakravarthy's lost sister Sudha. Chakravathy starts feeling that his sister has returned in the form of Madhavi. He feels relief in visiting their house and speaking to Madhavi so that it's like speaking to his own sister. Though Madhavi finds Chakravarthy's behavior a little odd in the beginning, her husband convinces her, saying Chakravarthy is a very good gentleman.\n\nMeanwhile, Nirmala despises the affection of Chakravarthy towards Madhavi's family. On the ill advice of the cook ([[Suryakantham]]), Nirmala writes a secret letter to Ravindra by wrongly quoting the friendship of Chakravarthy and Madhavi. Ravindra starts believing the cooked up story and hates Chakravarthy. He insults Madhavi without even considering that the latter is pregnant and in a weakened condition. As the story reaches its climax, Ravindra realizes that Chakravarthy only had brotherly affection, but nothing else on Madhavi. Nirmala realizes her mistake of writing such a letter. Ravindra realizes his blunder and even names his newborn son after Chakravarthy.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Akkineni Nageswara Rao]] as Dr. Chakravarthy\n*[[Savitri (actress)|Savitri]] as Madhavi\n*[[Jaggayya (actor)|Jaggayya]] as Ravindra\n*[[Krishna Kumari (actress)|Krishna Kumari]] as Dr. Sridevi\n*[[Sowcar Janaki]] as Nirmala\n*[[Gummadi Venkateswara Rao|Gummadi]] as Inspector Sridhar\n*[[Padmanabham]] as Venkata Swamy\n*[[Chalam]] as Venkata Ramana\n*[[Suryakantham]] as Kanthamma\n*[[Geetanjali (actress)|Geethanjali]] as Sudha\n*[[Jayanthi (actress)|Jayanthi]] as Padma\n\n==Crew==\n*'''Art''': G. V. Subba Rao\n*'''Choreography''': Hiralal, Pasumarthi \n*'''Lyrics''': Athreya, Arudra, Sri Sri, Dasarathi, Kosaraju\n*'''Story''': Koduri Kousalya Devi \n*'''Dialogues''': Gollapudi Maruthi Rao, Athreya \n*'''Music''': [[Saluri Rajeswara Rao]]\n*'''Play-back''': Ghantasala, P. Susheela, S. Janaki, P. B. Srinivas, Madhavapeddi Satyam, Vasantha\n*'''Cinematography''': P. S.  Selvaraj\n*'''Editing''': T. Krishna \n*'''Assistant Director''': [[K. Viswanath]]\n*'''Producer''': [[D. Madhusudhana Rao]]\n*'''Director''': [[Adurthi Subba Rao]]\n*'''Banner''': Annapurna Pictures\n*'''Release Date''': 10 July 1964\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Doctor Chakravarty\n| type       = film\n| artist     = [[Saluri Rajeswara Rao]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = 1964\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = Soundtrack\n| length     = 34:47\n| label      =\n| producer   = [[Saluri Rajeswara Rao]]\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!S. No.!!Song Title !!Lyrics !!Singers !!length\n|-\n|1\n|\"Manasuna Manasai\"\n|[[Sri Sri (writer)|Sri Sri]]\n|[[Ghantasala (singer)|Ghantasala]]\n|3:47\n|-\n|2\n|\"Ee Mounam Ee Bidiyam\"\n|[[Aarudhra]] \n|Ghantasala, [[P. Susheela]]\n|3:22\n|-\n|3\n|\"Neevuleka Veena\"\n|[[Aatreya (playwright)|Acharya Aatreya]]\n|P. Susheela\n|3:28\n|-\n|4\n|\"Paadamani Naanadagavalena\"\n|Aarudhra\n|P. Susheela\n|3:45\n|-\n|5\n|\"Nijam Cheppave Pilla\"\n|Aarudhra\n|P. Susheela, B. Vasantha\n|4:10\n|-\n|6\n|\"Paadamani Naanadaga Thaguna\"\n|Aarudhra\n|P. Susheela\n|3:30\n|-\n|7\n|\"Neevuleka Veena\" (Pathos) \n|Acharya Aatreya\n|P. Susheela\n|1:09\n|-\n|8\n|\"O Ungarala Mungurula Raja\"\n|Aarudhra\n|[[Madhavapeddi Satyam]], P. Susheela\n|4:32\n|-\n|9\n|\"Ontiga Samayam Chikkindhi\"\n|[[Kosaraju Raghavaiah|Kosaraju]]  \n|[[S. Janaki]], [[P. B. Sreenivas]]\n|3:24\n|-\n|10\n|\"Evaro Jwalanu Ragilincharu\"\n|Acharya Aatreya\n|Ghantasala\n|3:40\n|}\n\n==Awards==\n* [[National Film Award for Best Feature Film in Telugu]] - 1964\n* [[Nandi Award for Best Feature Film]] - 1964\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0260868}}\n\n{{National Film Award Best Feature Film Telugu}}\n\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:1964 films]]\n[[Category:1960s Telugu-language films]]\n[[Category:Indian drama films]]\n[[Category:Films based on Indian novels]]\n[[Category:Nandi Award winners]]\n[[Category:1960s drama films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Adurthi Subba Rao]]\n[[Category:Best Telugu Feature Film National Film Award winners]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Doctor Chakravarthy\n| image          = Doctor_Chakravarty.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| writer         = [[Acharya Atreya]]<br>[[Gollapudi Maruti Rao]] {{small|(dialogues)}}\n| story          = Koduri Kousalya Devi \n| screenplay     = Adurthi Subba Rao\n| producer       = [[D. Madhusudhana Rao]]\n| director       = [[Adurthi Subba Rao]]\n| starring       = [[Akkineni Nageswara Rao]]<br />[[Savitri (actress)|Savitri]]<br />[[Kongara Jaggaiah|Jaggaiah]]<br /> [[Sowcar Janaki]]\n| music          = [[Saluri Rajeswara Rao]]\n| cinematography = P. S. Selvaraj\n| editing        = T. Krishna\n| based on       = ''Chakrabharmanam'' {{small|(Novel)}}\n| studio         = Annapurna Pictures\n| released       = {{Film date|df=y|1964|7|10}}\n| runtime        = 167 mins\n| country        = India\n| language       = Telugu\n| budget         =\n| gross          = \n}}\n\n'''''Doctor Chakravarthy''''' is 1964 [[Telugu cinema|Telugu]] [[drama film]], produced by [[D. Madhusudhana Rao]] under the Annapurna Pictures banner and directed by [[Adurthi Subba Rao]]. It stars [[Akkineni Nageswara Rao]], [[Savitri (actress)|Savitri]],  [[Kongara Jaggaiah|Jaggaiah]] in the lead roles and music composed by [[Saluri Rajeswara Rao]]. The film is based on Koduri Kousalya Devi's  ''Chakrabhramanam'' (Novel). The film was recorded as an ''Industry Hit'' at the box office. It is the first film to win the [[Nandi Award]], instituted by [[Government of Andhra Pradesh]] in 1964. It inspired many people in India to become doctors.<ref>[http://www.chitramala.com/articles/tollywood-4063.html Telugu Articles - Chitramala.com<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100130192602/http://www.chitramala.com/articles/tollywood-4063.html |date=30 January 2010 }}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nDr. Chakravarthy ([[Akkineni Nageswara Rao]]) arrives from abroad and plans to marry his lady love Dr. Sridevi ([[Krishna Kumari (actress)|Krishna Kumari]]). He has an affectionate sister  Sudha ([[Geetanjali (actress)|Geethanjali]]). Chakravarthy is extremely fond of his sister. Sudha is a great musician and loves writing poetry and she gets married to a loving person. However, by the time Chakravarthy returns to his hometown, his sister is terribly ill and in the last stages of her life. Chakravarthy gets distraught to know that his sister has cancer. Sudha requests Chakravarthy to marry her sister-in-law Nirmala ([[Sowcar Janaki]]) as a dying wish. Chakravarthy doesn't get a chance to tell that he has already loved a woman in life. He suppresses the sadness and marries Nirmala as per his sister's wish. Nirmala is a materialistic person who loves going around for picnics, shopping and doesn't understand the artistic subtleties in life. Chakravarthy is a busy doctor with nonstop work dealing with patients, treatment and tests. He has nothing in common with Nirmala and their life goes on in a mechanical way, despite staying under one roof. The story makes a turn when Chakravarthy meets Ravindra ([[Jaggayya (actor)|Jaggayya]]) and his wife Madhavi ([[Savitri (actress)|Savitri]]). Madhavi is a great veena player and writes poetry exactly like Chakravarthy's lost sister Sudha. Chakravathy starts feeling that his sister has returned in the form of Madhavi. He feels relief in visiting their house and speaking to Madhavi so that it's like speaking to his own sister. Though Madhavi finds Chakravarthy's behavior a little odd in the beginning, her husband convinces her, saying Chakravarthy is a very good gentleman.\n\nMeanwhile, Nirmala despises the affection of Chakravarthy towards Madhavi's family. On the ill advice of the cook ([[Suryakantham]]), Nirmala writes a secret letter to Ravindra by wrongly quoting the friendship of Chakravarthy and Madhavi. Ravindra starts believing the cooked up story and hates Chakravarthy. He insults Madhavi without even considering that the latter is pregnant and in a weakened condition. As the story reaches its climax, Ravindra realizes that Chakravarthy only had brotherly affection, but nothing else on Madhavi. Nirmala realizes her mistake of writing such a letter. Ravindra realizes his blunder and even names his newborn son after Chakravarthy.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Akkineni Nageswara Rao]] as Dr. Chakravarthy\n*[[Savitri (actress)|Savitri]] as Madhavi\n*[[Jaggayya (actor)|Jaggayya]] as Ravindra\n*[[Krishna Kumari (actress)|Krishna Kumari]] as Dr. Sridevi\n*[[Sowcar Janaki]] as Nirmala\n*[[Gummadi Venkateswara Rao|Gummadi]] as Inspector Sridhar\n*[[Padmanabham]] as Venkata Swamy\n*[[Chalam]] as Venkata Ramana\n*[[Suryakantham]] as Kanthamma\n*[[Geetanjali (actress)|Geethanjali]] as Sudha\n*[[Jayanthi (actress)|Jayanthi]] as Padma\n\n==Crew==\n*'''Art''': G. V. Subba Rao\n*'''Choreography''': Hiralal, Pasumarthi \n*'''Lyrics''': Athreya, Arudra, Sri Sri, Dasarathi, Kosaraju\n*'''Story''': Koduri Kousalya Devi \n*'''Dialogues''': Gollapudi Maruthi Rao, Athreya \n*'''Music''': [[Saluri Rajeswara Rao]]\n*'''Play-back''': Ghantasala, P. Susheela, S. Janaki, P. B. Srinivas, Madhavapeddi Satyam, Vasantha\n*'''Cinematography''': P. S.  Selvaraj\n*'''Editing''': T. Krishna \n*'''Assistant Director''': [[K. Viswanath]]\n*'''Producer''': [[D. Madhusudhana Rao]]\n*'''Director''': [[Adurthi Subba Rao]]\n*'''Banner''': Annapurna Pictures\n*'''Release Date''': 10 July 1964\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Doctor Chakravarty\n| type       = film\n| artist     = [[Saluri Rajeswara Rao]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = 1964\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = Soundtrack\n| length     = 34:47\n| label      =\n| producer   = [[Saluri Rajeswara Rao]]\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!S. No.!!Song Title !!Lyrics !!Singers !!length\n|-\n|1\n|\"Manasuna Manasai\"\n|[[Sri Sri (writer)|Sri Sri]]\n|[[Ghantasala (singer)|Ghantasala]]\n|3:47\n|-\n|2\n|\"Ee Mounam Ee Bidiyam\"\n|[[Aarudhra]] \n|Ghantasala, [[P. Susheela]]\n|3:22\n|-\n|3\n|\"Neevuleka Veena\"\n|[[Aatreya (playwright)|Acharya Aatreya]]\n|P. Susheela\n|3:28\n|-\n|4\n|\"Paadamani Naanadagavalena\"\n|Aarudhra\n|P. Susheela\n|3:45\n|-\n|5\n|\"Nijam Cheppave Pilla\"\n|Aarudhra\n|P. Susheela, B. Vasantha\n|4:10\n|-\n|6\n|\"Paadamani Naanadaga Thaguna\"\n|Aarudhra\n|P. Susheela\n|3:30\n|-\n|7\n|\"Neevuleka Veena\" (Pathos) \n|Acharya Aatreya\n|P. Susheela\n|1:09\n|-\n|8\n|\"O Ungarala Mungurula Raja\"\n|Aarudhra\n|[[Madhavapeddi Satyam]], P. Susheela\n|4:32\n|-\n|9\n|\"Ontiga Samayam Chikkindhi\"\n|[[Kosaraju Raghavaiah|Kosaraju]]  \n|[[S. Janaki]], [[P. B. Sreenivas]]\n|3:24\n|-\n|10\n|\"Evaro Jwalanu Ragilincharu\"\n|Acharya Aatreya\n|Ghantasala\n|3:40\n|}\n\n==Awards==\n* [[National Film Award for Best Feature Film in Telugu]] - 1964\n* [[Nandi Award for Best Feature Film]] - 1964\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0260868}}\n\n{{National Film Award Best Feature Film Telugu}}\n\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:1964 films]]\n[[Category:1960s Telugu-language films]]\n[[Category:Indian drama films]]\n[[Category:Films based on Indian novels]]\n[[Category:Nandi Award winners]]\n[[Category:1960s drama films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Adurthi Subba Rao]]\n[[Category:Best Telugu Feature Film National Film Award winners]]\n", "name_user": "Jellysandwich0", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Doctor_Chakravarty"}
{"title_page": "2000 OFC Nations Cup Final", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox football match\n| title                   = 2000 OFC Nations Cup Final\n| event                   = [[2000 OFC Nations Cup]]\n| team1                   = [[Australia national association football team|Australia]]\n| team1association        = {{flagicon|Australia|size=30px}}\n| team1score              = 2\n| team2                   = [[New Zealand national football team|New Zealand]]\n| team2association        = {{flagicon|New Zealand|size=30px}}\n| team2score              = 0\n| details                 = \n| date                    = 28 June 2000\n| stadium                 = [[Stade Pater]]\n| city                    = [[Papeete]]\n| man_of_the_match1a      = \n| referee                 = [[Harry Attison]] \n| attendance              = \n| weather                 = \n| previous                = [[1998 OFC Nations Cup Final|1998]]\n| next                    = [[2002 OFC Nations Cup Final|2002]]\n}}\n\nThe '''2000 OFC Nations Cup Final''' was an [[Association football|association football]] match that took place on 28 June 2000 at the [[Stade Pater]], [[Papeete]]. It was the final of the [[2000 OFC Nations Cup]] which was the fifth edition of the [[OFC Nations Cup]], a international competition for national teams in the [[Oceania Football Confederation]].\n\nIt was contested between [[Australia national soccer team|Australia]] and [[New Zealand national football team|New Zealand]] in what was a repeat of the [[1998 OFC Nations Cup Final|1998 final]] which New Zealand won. This was also New Zealand's third appearance in a contentinal final after also appearing in the [[1973 OFC Nations Cup Final|1973 final]] which they won.<ref name=\"OFC overall rsssf\">{{cite web | url=http://www.rsssf.com/tableso/oceania-cup.html | title=Oceanian Nations Cup | publisher=[[rsssf.com]] | accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> For Australia, this was their fourth appearance in the final with Australia also winning the [[1980 OFC Nations Cup|1980]] and [[1996 OFC Nations Cup Final|1996]].<ref name=\"OFC overall rsssf\"/> After both teams won their respective groups, Australia defeated [[Vanuatu national football team|Vanuatu]] while New Zealand defeated the [[Solomon Islands national football team|Solomon Islands]].<ref name=\"rsssf\">{{cite web | url=http://www.rsssf.com/tables/00oc.html | title=Oceanian Nations Cup 2000 | publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|rsssf.com]] | accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn the final, goals from [[Shaun Murphy]] and [[Craig Foster]] gave Australia a 2\u20130 win over New Zealand to record their third OFC title. This also meant that as winners of the Nations Cup, they also qualified for the [[2001 FIFA Confederations Cup]] which was held in South Korea and Japan as representative of the OFC.\n\n==Route to the final==\n{{main|2000 OFC Nations Cup}}\n{| style=\"width:100%;text-align:center\"\n|- style=\"vertical-align:top;background:#9cf\"\n!colspan=2 style=\"width:1*\"|Australia\n!Round\n!colspan=2 style=\"width:1*\"|New Zealand\n|- style=\"vertical-align:top;background:#c1e0ff\"\n|Opponent\n|Result\n||[[2000 OFC Nations Cup#Group stage|Group stage]]\n|Opponent\n|Result\n|-\n|{{fb|COK}}\n|[[2000 OFC Nations Cup#Group A|17\u20130]]\n|style=\"background:#c1e0ff\"|Match 1\n|{{fb|TAH}}\n|[[2000 OFC Nations Cup#Group B|2\u20130]]\n|-\n|{{fb|SOL}}\n|[[2000 OFC Nations Cup#Group A|6\u20130]]\n|style=\"background:#c1e0ff\"|Match 2\n|{{fb|VAN}}\n|[[2000 OFC Nations Cup#Group B|3\u20131]]\n|-\n|colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\"|'''[[2000 OFC Nations Cup#Group A|Group A]] winner'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!width=\"190\"|Team\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip|Pld|Played}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip|W|Won}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip|D|Drawn}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip|L|Lost}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip|GF|Goals for}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip|GA|Goals against}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip|GD|Goal difference}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip|Pts|Points}}\n|- style=\"background:#cfc\"\n|align=left|'''{{fb|AUS}}'''\n|2||2||0||0||23||0||+23||'''6'''\n|- style=\"background:#cfc\"\n|align=left|{{fb|SOL}}\n|2||1||0||1||5||7||\u22122||'''3'''\n|-\n|align=left|{{fb|COK}}\n|2||0||0||2||1||22||\u221221||'''0'''\n|}\n|style=\"background:#c1e0ff\"|Final standings\n|colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\"|'''[[2000 OFC Nations Cup#Group B|Group B]] winner'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!width=\"190\"|Team\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip|Pld|Played}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip|W|Won}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip|D|Drawn}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip|L|Lost}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip|GF|Goals for}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip|GA|Goals against}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip|GD|Goal difference}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip|Pts|Points}}\n|- style=\"background:#cfc\"\n|align=left|'''{{fb|NZL}}'''\n|2||2||0||0||5||1||+4||'''6'''\n|- style=\"background:#cfc\"\n|align=left|{{fb|VAN}}\n|2||1||0||1||4||5||\u22121||'''3'''\n|-\n|align=left|{{fb|TAH}}\n|2||0||0||2||2||5||\u22123||'''0'''\n|}\n|- style=\"vertical-align:top;background:#c1e0ff\"\n|Opponent\n|Result\n||[[2000 OFC Nations Cup#Knockout stage|Knockout stage]]\n|Opponent\n|Result\n|-\n|{{fb|VAN}}\n|[[2000 OFC Nations Cup#Semifinals|1\u20130]]\n|style=\"background:#c1e0ff\"|Semi-finals\n|{{fb|SOL}}\n|[[2000 OFC Nations Cup#Semifinals|2\u20130]]\n|}\n===Australia===\nAs finalists in the [[1998 OFC Nations Cup]], and the [[Oceania Football Confederation|OFC]]'s top-ranked side, the \"[[Australia national association football team|Socceroos]]\" were given entry straight into the tournament finals. They progressed comfortably through the group stage, accounting for [[Cook Islands national football team|Cook Islands]] and [[Solomon Islands national football team|Solomon Islands]] comfortably 17-0 and 6-0 respectively. In the semi-final, they played [[Vanuatu national football team|Vanuatu]], winning 1-0 in a match that was closer than expected. Australia's [[Clayton Zane]] was the tournament's top scorer going into the final, with 5 goals.\n\n===New Zealand===\nLike Australia, New Zealand were given direct entry into the tournament finals, as [[1998 OFC Nations Cup]] champions and the [[Oceania Football Confederation|OFC]]'s second ranked side. They beat both [[Tahiti national football team|Tahiti]] and [[Vanuatu national football team|Vanuatu]] by 2 goals to progress from the group stage. In the semi-finals, they played [[Solomon Islands national football team|Solomon Islands]] and won 2-0 to move through to the final.\n\n==Pre-match==\n\n===Analysis===\nDespite New Zealand having won the [[1998 OFC Nations Cup]] final, Australia went into the game as favourites, ranked 15 spots ahead of New Zealand in [[FIFA World Rankings]].\n\n==Match==\n\n===First half===\nAustralia was the better side for much of the match, although New Zealand did create some chances. Australia took the lead 5 minutes from half time, as [[Shaun Murphy (footballer)|Shaun Murphy]] scored off a [[Stan Lazaridis]] corner.\n\n===Second half===\nAustralia's ascendency continued, and when [[Danny Tiatto]]'s cross was finished by [[Craig Foster (Australian footballer)|Craig Foster]] midway through the second half, the result was all but secured for Australia.\n\n===Match details===\n{{football box\n| date         = 28 June 2000\n| event        = \n| round        = \n| time         = 18:00\n| team1        = {{fb-rt|Australia}}\n| score        = 2\u20130\n| aet          = \n| report       = [http://www.ozfootball.net/ark/Socceroo/reports/vNZ2000a.html Report]\n| team2        = {{fb|New Zealand}}\n| goals1       = [[Shaun Murphy (footballer)|Shaun Murphy]] {{goal|40}} <br/> [[Craig Foster (Australian footballer)|Craig Foster]] {{goal|66}}\n| goals2       = \n| stadium      = [[Stade Pater]], [[Papeete]]\n| attendance   = 300\n| referee      = [[Harry Attison]]\n}}\n\n{| width=92% |\n|-\n|{{Football kit\n| pattern_la = _goldshoulders\n| pattern_b  = _goldenvertical\n| pattern_ra = _goldshoulders\n| pattern_sh = _goldsides\n| pattern_so = _color_3_stripes_yellow\n| leftarm    = 355E3B\n| body       = 355E3B\n| rightarm   = 355E3B\n| shorts     = 355E3B\n| socks      = 355E3B\n| alt        = a green shirt with gold trim, green shorts, and green socks\n| title      = Australia\n}}\n|{{Football kit\n| pattern_la = _blackline\n| pattern_b  = _blackshoulders\n| pattern_ra = _blackline\n| pattern_sh = _white stripes\n| pattern_so = _band_black\n| leftarm    = FFFFFF\n| body       = FFFFFF\n| rightarm   = FFFFFF\n| shorts     = 000000\n| socks      = FFFFFF\n| alt        = a white shirt with black trim, black shorts, and white socks\n| title      = New Zealand\n}}\n|}\n\n{| width=\"100%\"\n|valign=\"top\" width=\"40%\"|\n{| style=\"font-size: 90%\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\"\n|colspan=\"4\"|{{flagicon|Australia|size=100px}}<br />'''AUSTRALIA:'''\n|-\n!width=25| !!width=25|\n|-\n|GK ||'''1''' || [[Zeljko Kalac]] \n|-\n|DF ||'''2''' || [[Kevin Muscat]] \n|-\n|DF ||'''3'''|| [[Shaun Murphy (footballer)|Shaun Murphy]] || {{goal|40}}\n|-\n|DF ||'''5''' || [[Tony Popovic]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''7'''|| [[Danny Tiatto]] \n|-\n|MF ||'''8'''|| [[Stan Lazaridis]] \n|-\n|MF ||'''4''' || [[Paul Okon]] \n|-\n|MF ||'''6''' || [[Craig Foster (Australian footballer)|Craig Foster]] || {{goal|66}} || {{suboff|80}} \n|-\n|MF ||'''13'''|| [[Brett Emerton]] \n|-\n|FW ||'''9'''|| [[David Zdrillic]] \n|-\n|FW ||'''11''' || [[Paul Agostino]] || || {{suboff|80}}\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Substitutes:'''\n|-\n|MF ||'''14'''|| [[Aurelio Vidmar]] || || {{subon|80}} \n|-\n|FW ||'''15'''|| [[Clayton Zane]] || || {{subon|80}}\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Manager:'''\n|-\n|colspan=4| [[Frank Farina]]\n|}\n|valign=\"top\"|<small></small>\n|valign=\"top\" width=\"50%\"|\n{| style=\"font-size: 90%\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" align=\"center\"\n|colspan=\"4\"|{{flagicon|New Zealand|size=100px}}<br />'''NEW ZEALAND:'''\n|-\n!width=25| !!width=25|\n|-\n|GK ||'''1''' || [[Jason Batty]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''2'''|| [[Che Bunce]] \n|-\n|DF ||'''3''' || [[Sean Douglas (footballer)|Sean Douglas]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''5'''|| [[Jonathan Perry (footballer)|Jonathan Perry]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''6''' || [[Gavin Wilkinson]] || {{yel|27}} || {{suboff|70}}\n|-\n|DF ||'''18''' || [[Scott Smith (footballer born 1975)|Scott Smith]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''7''' || [[Simon Elliott]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''10'''|| [[Chris Jackson (New Zealand footballer)|Chris Jackson]] \n|-\n|MF ||'''12'''|| [[Mark Atkinson (footballer)|Mark Atkinson]] || || {{suboff|77}}\n|-\n|FW ||'''8'''|| [[Chris Killen]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''13'''|| [[Kris Bouckenooghe]]\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Substitutes:'''\n|-\n|MF ||'''16'''|| [[Raf de Gregorio]] || || {{subon|70}}\n|-\n|FW ||'''9'''|| [[Paul Urlovic]] || || {{subon|77}}\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Manager:'''\n|-\n|colspan=4| [[Ken Dugdale]]\n|}\n|}\n\n==Post match==\nAustralia's win qualified them for the [[2001 FIFA Confederations Cup]], and was their third [[OFC Nations Cup]] win their first since [[1996 OFC Nations Cup|1996]].\n\n==See also==\n* [[Australia\u2013New Zealand soccer rivalry]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.rsssf.com/tables/00oc.html RSSF].  Accessed 21 February 2010.\n* [https://www.fifa.com/newscentre/news/newsid=73198/ Fifa]\n\n{{Oceania Nations Cup}}\n{{Australia national football team matches}}\n{{New Zealand national football team matches}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:OFC Nations Cup Final}}\n[[Category:OFC Nations Cup Finals|2000]]\n[[Category:Football in French Polynesia]]\n[[Category:2000 OFC Nations Cup|Final]]\n[[Category:Australia national soccer team matches|2000]]\n[[Category:New Zealand national football team matches|2000]]\n[[Category:2000 in Australian soccer]]\n[[Category:2000 in New Zealand association football]]\n[[Category:2000 in French Polynesian sport]]\n[[Category:June 2000 sports events in Oceania]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox football match\n| title                   = 2000 OFC Nations Cup Final\n| event                   = [[2000 OFC Nations Cup]]\n| team1                   = [[Australia national association football team|Australia]]\n| team1association        = {{flagicon|Australia|size=30px}}\n| team1score              = 2\n| team2                   = [[New Zealand national football team|New Zealand]]\n| team2association        = {{flagicon|New Zealand|size=30px}}\n| team2score              = 0\n| details                 = \n| date                    = 28 June 2000\n| stadium                 = [[Stade Pater]]\n| city                    = [[Papeete]]\n| man_of_the_match1a      = \n| referee                 = [[Harry Attison]] \n| attendance              = \n| weather                 = \n| previous                = [[1998 OFC Nations Cup Final|1998]]\n| next                    = [[2002 OFC Nations Cup Final|2002]]\n}}\n\nThe '''2000 OFC Nations Cup Final''' was an [[Association football|association football]] match that took place on 28 June 2000 at the [[Stade Pater]], [[Papeete]]. It was the final of the [[2000 OFC Nations Cup]] which was the fifth edition of the [[OFC Nations Cup]], a international competition for national teams in the [[Oceania Football Confederation]].\n\nIt was contested between [[Australia national soccer team|Australia]] and [[New Zealand national football team|New Zealand]] in what was a repeat of the [[1998 OFC Nations Cup Final|1998 final]] which New Zealand won. This was also New Zealand's third appearance in a contentinal final after also appearing in the [[1973 OFC Nations Cup Final|1973 final]] which they won.<ref name=\"OFC overall rsssf\">{{cite web | url=http://www.rsssf.com/tableso/oceania-cup.html | title=Oceanian Nations Cup | publisher=[[rsssf.com]] | accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> For Australia, this was their fourth appearance in the final with Australia also winning the [[1980 OFC Nations Cup|1980]] and [[1996 OFC Nations Cup Final|1996]].<ref name=\"OFC overall rsssf\"/> After both teams won their respective groups, Australia defeated [[Vanuatu national football team|Vanuatu]] while New Zealand defeated the [[Solomon Islands national football team|Solomon Islands]].<ref name=\"rsssf\">{{cite web | url=http://www.rsssf.com/tables/00oc.html | title=Oceanian Nations Cup 2000 | publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|rsssf.com]] | accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn the final, goals from [[Shaun Murphy]] and [[Craig Foster]] gave Australia a 2\u20130 win over New Zealand to record their third OFC title. This also meant that as winners of the Nations Cup, they also qualified for the [[2001 FIFA Confederations Cup]] which was held in South Korea and Japan as representative of the OFC.\n\n==Route to the final==\n{{main|2000 OFC Nations Cup}}\n{| style=\"width:100%;text-align:center\"\n|- style=\"vertical-align:top;background:#9cf\"\n!colspan=2 style=\"width:1*\"|Australia\n!Round\n!colspan=2 style=\"width:1*\"|New Zealand\n|- style=\"vertical-align:top;background:#c1e0ff\"\n|Opponent\n|Result\n||[[2000 OFC Nations Cup#Group stage|Group stage]]\n|Opponent\n|Result\n|-\n|{{fb|COK}}\n|[[2000 OFC Nations Cup#Group A|17\u20130]]\n|style=\"background:#c1e0ff\"|Match 1\n|{{fb|TAH}}\n|[[2000 OFC Nations Cup#Group B|2\u20130]]\n|-\n|{{fb|SOL}}\n|[[2000 OFC Nations Cup#Group A|6\u20130]]\n|style=\"background:#c1e0ff\"|Match 2\n|{{fb|VAN}}\n|[[2000 OFC Nations Cup#Group B|3\u20131]]\n|-\n|colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\"|'''[[2000 OFC Nations Cup#Group A|Group A]] winner'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!width=\"190\"|Team\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip|Pld|Played}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip|W|Won}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip|D|Drawn}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip|L|Lost}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip|GF|Goals for}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip|GA|Goals against}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip|GD|Goal difference}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip|Pts|Points}}\n|- style=\"background:#cfc\"\n|align=left|'''{{fb|AUS}}'''\n|2||2||0||0||23||0||+23||'''6'''\n|- style=\"background:#cfc\"\n|align=left|{{fb|SOL}}\n|2||1||0||1||5||7||\u22122||'''3'''\n|-\n|align=left|{{fb|COK}}\n|2||0||0||2||1||22||\u221221||'''0'''\n|}\n|style=\"background:#c1e0ff\"|Final standings\n|colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\"|'''[[2000 OFC Nations Cup#Group B|Group B]] winner'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!width=\"190\"|Team\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip|Pld|Played}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip|W|Won}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip|D|Drawn}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip|L|Lost}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip|GF|Goals for}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip|GA|Goals against}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip|GD|Goal difference}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip|Pts|Points}}\n|- style=\"background:#cfc\"\n|align=left|{{fb|NZL}}'''\n|2||2||0||0||5||1||+4||'''6'''\n|- style=\"background:#cfc\"\n|align=left|{{fb|VAN}}\n|2||1||0||1||4||5||\u22121||'''3'''\n|-\n|align=left|{{fb|TAH}}\n|2||0||0||2||2||5||\u22123||'''0'''\n|}\n|- style=\"vertical-align:top;background:#c1e0ff\"\n|Opponent\n|Result\n||[[2000 OFC Nations Cup#Knockout stage|Knockout stage]]\n|Opponent\n|Result\n|-\n|{{fb|VAN}}\n|[[2000 OFC Nations Cup#Semifinals|1\u20130]]\n|style=\"background:#c1e0ff\"|Semi-finals\n|{{fb|SOL}}\n|[[2000 OFC Nations Cup#Semifinals|2\u20130]]\n|}\n===Australia===\nAs finalists in the [[1998 OFC Nations Cup]], and the [[Oceania Football Confederation|OFC]]'s top-ranked side, the \"[[Australia national association football team|Socceroos]]\" were given entry straight into the tournament finals. They progressed comfortably through the group stage, accounting for [[Cook Islands national football team|Cook Islands]] and [[Solomon Islands national football team|Solomon Islands]] comfortably 17-0 and 6-0 respectively. In the semi-final, they played [[Vanuatu national football team|Vanuatu]], winning 1-0 in a match that was closer than expected. Australia's [[Clayton Zane]] was the tournament's top scorer going into the final, with 5 goals.\n\n===New Zealand===\nLike Australia, New Zealand were given direct entry into the tournament finals, as [[1998 OFC Nations Cup]] champions and the [[Oceania Football Confederation|OFC]]'s second ranked side. They beat both [[Tahiti national football team|Tahiti]] and [[Vanuatu national football team|Vanuatu]] by 2 goals to progress from the group stage. In the semi-finals, they played [[Solomon Islands national football team|Solomon Islands]] and won 2-0 to move through to the final.\n\n==Pre-match==\n\n===Analysis===\nDespite New Zealand having won the [[1998 OFC Nations Cup]] final, Australia went into the game as favourites, ranked 15 spots ahead of New Zealand in [[FIFA World Rankings]].\n\n==Match==\n\n===First half===\nAustralia was the better side for much of the match, although New Zealand did create some chances. Australia took the lead 5 minutes from half time, as [[Shaun Murphy (footballer)|Shaun Murphy]] scored off a [[Stan Lazaridis]] corner.\n\n===Second half===\nAustralia's ascendency continued, and when [[Danny Tiatto]]'s cross was finished by [[Craig Foster (Australian footballer)|Craig Foster]] midway through the second half, the result was all but secured for Australia.\n\n===Match details===\n{{football box\n| date         = 28 June 2000\n| event        = \n| round        = \n| time         = 18:00\n| team1        = {{fb-rt|Australia}}\n| score        = 2\u20130\n| aet          = \n| report       = [http://www.ozfootball.net/ark/Socceroo/reports/vNZ2000a.html Report]\n| team2        = {{fb|New Zealand}}\n| goals1       = [[Shaun Murphy (footballer)|Shaun Murphy]] {{goal|40}} <br/> [[Craig Foster (Australian footballer)|Craig Foster]] {{goal|66}}\n| goals2       = \n| stadium      = [[Stade Pater]], [[Papeete]]\n| attendance   = 300\n| referee      = [[Harry Attison]]\n}}\n\n{| width=92% |\n|-\n|{{Football kit\n| pattern_la = _goldshoulders\n| pattern_b  = _goldenvertical\n| pattern_ra = _goldshoulders\n| pattern_sh = _goldsides\n| pattern_so = _color_3_stripes_yellow\n| leftarm    = 355E3B\n| body       = 355E3B\n| rightarm   = 355E3B\n| shorts     = 355E3B\n| socks      = 355E3B\n| alt        = a green shirt with gold trim, green shorts, and green socks\n| title      = Australia\n}}\n|{{Football kit\n| pattern_la = _blackline\n| pattern_b  = _blackshoulders\n| pattern_ra = _blackline\n| pattern_sh = _white stripes\n| pattern_so = _band_black\n| leftarm    = FFFFFF\n| body       = FFFFFF\n| rightarm   = FFFFFF\n| shorts     = 000000\n| socks      = FFFFFF\n| alt        = a white shirt with black trim, black shorts, and white socks\n| title      = New Zealand\n}}\n|}\n\n{| width=\"100%\"\n|valign=\"top\" width=\"40%\"|\n{| style=\"font-size: 90%\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\"\n|colspan=\"4\"|{{flagicon|Australia|size=100px}}<br />'''AUSTRALIA:'''\n|-\n!width=25| !!width=25|\n|-\n|GK ||'''1''' || [[Zeljko Kalac]] \n|-\n|DF ||'''2''' || [[Kevin Muscat]] \n|-\n|DF ||'''3'''|| [[Shaun Murphy (footballer)|Shaun Murphy]] || {{goal|40}}\n|-\n|DF ||'''5''' || [[Tony Popovic]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''7'''|| [[Danny Tiatto]] \n|-\n|MF ||'''8'''|| [[Stan Lazaridis]] \n|-\n|MF ||'''4''' || [[Paul Okon]] \n|-\n|MF ||'''6''' || [[Craig Foster (Australian footballer)|Craig Foster]] || {{goal|66}} || {{suboff|80}} \n|-\n|MF ||'''13'''|| [[Brett Emerton]] \n|-\n|FW ||'''9'''|| [[David Zdrillic]] \n|-\n|FW ||'''11''' || [[Paul Agostino]] || || {{suboff|80}}\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Substitutes:'''\n|-\n|MF ||'''14'''|| [[Aurelio Vidmar]] || || {{subon|80}} \n|-\n|FW ||'''15'''|| [[Clayton Zane]] || || {{subon|80}}\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Manager:'''\n|-\n|colspan=4| [[Frank Farina]]\n|}\n|valign=\"top\"|<small></small>\n|valign=\"top\" width=\"50%\"|\n{| style=\"font-size: 90%\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" align=\"center\"\n|colspan=\"4\"|{{flagicon|New Zealand|size=100px}}<br />'''NEW ZEALAND:'''\n|-\n!width=25| !!width=25|\n|-\n|GK ||'''1''' || [[Jason Batty]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''2'''|| [[Che Bunce]] \n|-\n|DF ||'''3''' || [[Sean Douglas (footballer)|Sean Douglas]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''5'''|| [[Jonathan Perry (footballer)|Jonathan Perry]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''6''' || [[Gavin Wilkinson]] || {{yel|27}} || {{suboff|70}}\n|-\n|DF ||'''18''' || [[Scott Smith (footballer born 1975)|Scott Smith]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''7''' || [[Simon Elliott]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''10'''|| [[Chris Jackson (New Zealand footballer)|Chris Jackson]] \n|-\n|MF ||'''12'''|| [[Mark Atkinson (footballer)|Mark Atkinson]] || || {{suboff|77}}\n|-\n|FW ||'''8'''|| [[Chris Killen]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''13'''|| [[Kris Bouckenooghe]]\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Substitutes:'''\n|-\n|MF ||'''16'''|| [[Raf de Gregorio]] || || {{subon|70}}\n|-\n|FW ||'''9'''|| [[Paul Urlovic]] || || {{subon|77}}\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Manager:'''\n|-\n|colspan=4| [[Ken Dugdale]]\n|}\n|}\n\n==Post match==\nAustralia's win qualified them for the [[2001 FIFA Confederations Cup]], and was their third [[OFC Nations Cup]] win their first since [[1996 OFC Nations Cup|1996]].\n\n==See also==\n* [[Australia\u2013New Zealand soccer rivalry]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.rsssf.com/tables/00oc.html RSSF].  Accessed 21 February 2010.\n* [https://www.fifa.com/newscentre/news/newsid=73198/ Fifa]\n\n{{Oceania Nations Cup}}\n{{Australia national football team matches}}\n{{New Zealand national football team matches}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:OFC Nations Cup Final}}\n[[Category:OFC Nations Cup Finals|2000]]\n[[Category:Football in French Polynesia]]\n[[Category:2000 OFC Nations Cup|Final]]\n[[Category:Australia national soccer team matches|2000]]\n[[Category:New Zealand national football team matches|2000]]\n[[Category:2000 in Australian soccer]]\n[[Category:2000 in New Zealand association football]]\n[[Category:2000 in French Polynesian sport]]\n[[Category:June 2000 sports events in Oceania]]\n", "name_user": "HawkAussie", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRoute to the final", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2000_OFC_Nations_Cup_Final"}
{"title_page": "\u2018Akeke\u2018e", "text_new": "{{Speciesbox\n| name               = {{Okina}}Akeke{{Okina}}e\n| image              = Loxops caeruleirostris1.jpg\n| image_caption      = Male above, female below\n| status             = CR\n| status_system      = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref         = <ref name=IUCN>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22720832/0 |title=''Loxops caeruleirostris'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=26 November 2013}}</ref>\n| genus              = Loxops\n| species            = caeruleirostris\n| authority          = [[Scott Barchard Wilson|Wilson]], 1890\n}}\n\nThe '''''{{okina}}akeke{{okina}}e''''' (''Loxops caeruleirostris'') is a [[bird]] [[species]] in the [[family (biology)|family]] [[Fringillidae]], where it is placed in the [[Hawaiian honeycreeper]] [[genus]] ''[[Loxops]]''. It is [[endemism|endemic]] to the island of [[Kauai|Kaua{{okina}}i]] where it is found in small numbers in higher elevations. Because of their similar size, shape, and unusual bill, the {{okina}}akeke{{okina}}e and the [[\u02bbAkepa|{{okina}}akepa]] (''Loxops coccineus'') were for some time classified as a single species. This was eventually changed, because of differences in their color, nesting behavior, and calls.\n\n==Description and behavior==\nThe {{okina}}akeke{{okina}}e is a greenish-yellow bird with a black mask around the eye (especially prominent in the male) and a bluish bill, unlike the ''[[\u02bbAkepa|{{okina}}akepa]]'', which is usually red, canary-yellow or orange, without black, and has a horn-colored bill. The bill-tips are crossed over, though not bent as in the distantly-related [[crossbill]]s (''Loxia'').<ref name=fb>{{cite web |url=http://www.state.hi.us/dlnr/dofaw/cwcs/files/NAAT%20final%20CWCS/Chapters/Terrestrial%20Fact%20Sheets/Forest%20Birds/akekee%20NAAT%20final%20!.pdf |format=[[PDF]] |title=Forest Birds: \u02bbAkeke\u02bbe or Kaua\u02bbi \u02bb\u0100kepa |publisher=State of Hawai\u02bbi |date=2005-10-01 |accessdate=}}</ref> The {{okina}}akeke{{okina}}e uses its bill like scissors to cut open buds in search of insects to eat. It also feeds on the nectar of some trees. This bird builds nests primarily of twigs high up in trees, while the {{okina}}akepa uses tree cavities as nest sites.\n\n==Habitat==\nThe {{okina}}akeke{{okina}}e is currently found only in the [[Waimea Canyon State Park]], [[Alakai Wilderness Preserve|Alaka{{okina}}i Wilderness Preserve]] and [[Koke'e State Park|K\u014dke{{okina}}e State Park]]. It has been heading toward [[extinction]] because of its lack of tolerance to alteration of its [[habitat]], which is based on [[Hawaiian tropical rainforests#Mixed mesic forests|mesic]] and [[Hawaiian tropical rainforests#Wet forests|wet forests]], especially {{okina}}\u014dhi{{okina}}a lehua (''[[Metrosideros polymorpha]]'') trees.\n\n==Threats==\n[[File:Loxops caeruleirostris.jpg|thumb|left|170px]]\nThe {{okina}}akeke{{okina}}e is threatened by the introduction of plants like the banana p\u014dka (''[[Passiflora tarminiana]]''), a [[passionflower]] [[vine]], that displace the native plants. [[Feral pig]]s and [[feral goat]]s also destroy native growth. The lack of native host plants leads to the decline of the insects on which the {{okina}}akeke{{okina}}e feeds. [[Avian malaria]] (''Plasmodium relictum'') and [[fowlpox]] transmitted by accidentally introduced [[mosquito]]es continues to affect the {{okina}}akeke{{okina}}e, limiting its populations to habitat above 1,100 meters [[Above mean sea level|ASL]], where mosquitoes do not occur. Forest clearing in different parts of the island of Kaua{{okina}}i has caused the [[loss of habitat]] for this and many other bird species.<ref name=blfs>{{cite web |url=http://www.birdlife.org/datazone/species/index.html?action=SpcHTMDetails.asp&sid=8918&m=0 |title=BirdLife International (2009) Species factsheet: Loxops caeruleirostris. |accessdate=2010-01-30}}</ref>\n\nThe conservation status for this species was updated to [[critically endangered]] in 2008 due to a rapid decrease in population over the preceding decade. The 2012 population was estimated under 5,000 individuals<ref name=IUCN/> and in 2016 fewer than 1,000.<ref>[https://www.sciencenews.org/blog/wild-things/kauai%E2%80%99s-native-forest-birds-are-headed-toward-extinction Kauai\u2019s native forest birds are headed toward extinction] by Sarah Zielinski, published by \"Science News\" on September 13, 2016</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1302723}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Akekee}}\n[[Category:Loxops]]\n[[Category:Hawaiian honeycreepers]]\n[[Category:Endemic fauna of Hawaii]]\n[[Category:Critically endangered fauna of Hawaii]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1890]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Scott Barchard Wilson]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n[[Category:ESA endangered species]]\n", "text_old": "{{Speciesbox\n| name               = {{Okina}}Akeke{{Okina}}e\n| image              = Loxops caeruleirostris1.jpg\n| image_caption      = Male above, female below\n| status             = CR\n| status_system      = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref         = <ref name=IUCN>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22720832/0 |title=''Loxops caeruleirostris'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=26 November 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| genus              = Loxops\n| species            = caeruleirostris\n| authority          = [[Scott Barchard Wilson|Wilson]], 1890\n}}\n\nThe '''''{{okina}}akeke{{okina}}e''''' (''Loxops caeruleirostris'') is a [[bird]] [[species]] in the [[family (biology)|family]] [[Fringillidae]], where it is placed in the [[Hawaiian honeycreeper]] [[genus]] ''[[Loxops]]''. It is [[endemism|endemic]] to the island of [[Kauai|Kaua{{okina}}i]] where it is found in small numbers in higher elevations. Because of their similar size, shape, and unusual bill, the {{okina}}akeke{{okina}}e and the [[\u02bbAkepa|{{okina}}akepa]] (''Loxops coccineus'') were for some time classified as a single species. This was eventually changed, because of differences in their color, nesting behavior, and calls.\n\n==Description and behavior==\nThe {{okina}}akeke{{okina}}e is a greenish-yellow bird with a black mask around the eye (especially prominent in the male) and a bluish bill, unlike the ''[[\u02bbAkepa|{{okina}}akepa]]'', which is usually red, canary-yellow or orange, without black, and has a horn-colored bill. The bill-tips are crossed over, though not bent as in the distantly-related [[crossbill]]s (''Loxia'').<ref name=fb>{{cite web |url=http://www.state.hi.us/dlnr/dofaw/cwcs/files/NAAT%20final%20CWCS/Chapters/Terrestrial%20Fact%20Sheets/Forest%20Birds/akekee%20NAAT%20final%20!.pdf |format=[[PDF]] |title=Forest Birds: \u02bbAkeke\u02bbe or Kaua\u02bbi \u02bb\u0100kepa |publisher=State of Hawai\u02bbi |date=2005-10-01 |accessdate=}}</ref> The {{okina}}akeke{{okina}}e uses its bill like scissors to cut open buds in search of insects to eat. It also feeds on the nectar of some trees. This bird builds nests primarily of twigs high up in trees, while the {{okina}}akepa uses tree cavities as nest sites.\n\n==Habitat==\nThe {{okina}}akeke{{okina}}e is currently found only in the [[Waimea Canyon State Park]], [[Alakai Wilderness Preserve|Alaka{{okina}}i Wilderness Preserve]] and [[Koke'e State Park|K\u014dke{{okina}}e State Park]]. It has been heading toward [[extinction]] because of its lack of tolerance to alteration of its [[habitat]], which is based on [[Hawaiian tropical rainforests#Mixed mesic forests|mesic]] and [[Hawaiian tropical rainforests#Wet forests|wet forests]], especially {{okina}}\u014dhi{{okina}}a lehua (''[[Metrosideros polymorpha]]'') trees.\n\n==Threats==\n[[File:Loxops caeruleirostris.jpg|thumb|left|170px]]\nThe {{okina}}akeke{{okina}}e is threatened by the introduction of plants like the banana p\u014dka (''[[Passiflora tarminiana]]''), a [[passionflower]] [[vine]], that displace the native plants. [[Feral pig]]s and [[feral goat]]s also destroy native growth. The lack of native host plants leads to the decline of the insects on which the {{okina}}akeke{{okina}}e feeds. [[Avian malaria]] (''Plasmodium relictum'') and [[fowlpox]] transmitted by accidentally introduced [[mosquito]]es continues to affect the {{okina}}akeke{{okina}}e, limiting its populations to habitat above 1,100 meters [[Above mean sea level|ASL]], where mosquitoes do not occur. Forest clearing in different parts of the island of Kaua{{okina}}i has caused the [[loss of habitat]] for this and many other bird species.<ref name=blfs>{{cite web |url=http://www.birdlife.org/datazone/species/index.html?action=SpcHTMDetails.asp&sid=8918&m=0 |title=BirdLife International (2009) Species factsheet: Loxops caeruleirostris. |accessdate=2010-01-30}}</ref>\n\nThe conservation status for this species was updated to [[critically endangered]] in 2008 due to a rapid decrease in population over the preceding decade. The 2012 population was estimated under 5,000 individuals<ref name=IUCN/> and in 2016 fewer than 1,000.<ref>[https://www.sciencenews.org/blog/wild-things/kauai%E2%80%99s-native-forest-birds-are-headed-toward-extinction Kauai\u2019s native forest birds are headed toward extinction] by Sarah Zielinski, published by \"Science News\" on September 13, 2016</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1302723}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Akekee}}\n[[Category:Loxops]]\n[[Category:Hawaiian honeycreepers]]\n[[Category:Endemic fauna of Hawaii]]\n[[Category:Critically endangered fauna of Hawaii]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1890]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Scott Barchard Wilson]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n[[Category:ESA endangered species]]\n", "name_user": "Headbomb", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up, no longer needed, removed: |ref=harv", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%E2%80%98Akeke%E2%80%98e"}
{"title_page": "Omani Empire", "text_new": "{{Infobox former country\n|capital=[[Rustaq]]<br />{{small|(1692\u20131792)}}<br>[[Muscat]]<br />{{small|(1792\u20131840)}}<br>[[Zanzibar]]<br />{{small|(1840\u20131856)}}\n|common_languages='''Official:''' [[Arabic language|Arabic]]<br/>'''Regional:''' <br/>[[Persian language|Persian]]<br/>[[English language|English]]<br/>[[Swahili language|Swahili]]<br/>[[Omani Arabic]]<br/>[[Yemeni Arabic]]<br/>[[Balochi language|Balochi]]<br/>[[Somali language|Somali]]\n|common_name=Omani Empire\n|conventional_long_name=Omani Empire\n|currency=[[Dirham]]<br/>[[Indian rupee]]<br/>[[Maria Theresa thaler]]<br/>[[Shilling]]\n|date_event1=1718\n|event_start=Maritime Empire started by<br />[[Saif bin Sultan]]\n|event_end=Divided into<br />two Sultanates<br />\n|event1=Civil War<br />commenced\n|event2=Persian invasion<br />of [[Sohar]]\n|date_event2=1742\n|event3=[[House of Al Said|Al Busaid Dynasty]]<br /> took over\n|date_event3=1749\n|event4=Treaty with the<br />United States\n|date_event4=1837\n|deputy1=[[Ahmad bin Said al-Busaidi|Ahmad bin Said]]\n|deputy2=[[Said bin Ahmed]]\n|deputy3=Hamad bin Said\n|deputy4=Sultan bin Ahmed\n|deputy5=Badr bin Seif\n|deputy6=[[Said bin Sultan, Sultan of Muscat and Oman|Said bin Sultan]] {{small|(last)}}\n|flag_s1=Flag of Muscat.svg|flag_type=\n|image_flag=Om_1958.gif\n|image_coat=National emblem of Oman.svg\n|image_flag2=Flag of Muscat.svg\n|image_map=Empire of Oman.svg\n|image_map_caption={{small|'''Omani Empire at its peak under Said bin Sultan.'''}}\n<div style=\"text-align:left;\">\n|government_type={{nowrap|[[Monarchy]]}}\n|leader1=[[Saif bin Sultan]] {{small|(first)}}\n|leader2=[[Sultan bin Saif II]]\n|leader3=[[Saif bin Sultan II]]|leader4=[[Muhanna bin Sultan]]|leader5=[[Ya'arab bin Bel'arab]]|leader6=[[Muhammad bin Nasir]]|leader7=[[Sultan bin Murshid]]|leader8=[[Bal'arab bin Himyar]]\n|native_name={{lang|ar|\u0627\u0644\u0625\u0645\u0628\u0631\u0627\u0637\u0648\u0631\u064a\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0645\u0627\u0646\u064a\u0629}}\n|p1=Imamate of Oman\n|religion='''Dominant:'''<br/>[[Ibadi Islam]]<br/>'''Minor:'''<br/>[[Shia Islam]]<br/>[[Sunni Islam]]<br/>[[Christianity]]<br/>[[Hindu]]\n|s1=Muscat and Oman\n|s2=Sultanate of Zanzibar\n|s3=\n|s4=\n|year_start=1696\n|year_end=1856\n|year_leader1=1692\u20131711\n|year_leader2=1711\u20131718\n|year_leader3=1718\u20131719|year_leader4=1719\u20131720\n|year_leader5=1722\u20131723|year_leader6=1724\u20131728\n|year_leader7=1742\u20131743|year_leader8=1743\u20131749\n|year_deputy1=1744\u20131778\n|year_deputy2=1778\u20131783\n|year_deputy3=1783\u20131793\n|year_deputy4=1792\u20131804\n|year_deputy5=1805\u20131806|year_deputy6=1806\u20131856\n|status=Empire\n|flag_p1=Flag of The Imamate of Oman.svg\n|flag_s2=Flag of the Sultanate of Zanzibar (1963).svg\n|title_deputy=[[House of Al Said|Al Busaid Dynasty]]\n|title_leader=[[Yaruba dynasty|Yaruba Dynasty]]\n|stat_area1=1407118\n|stat_year1=1840 est.}}\n\n'''The Omani Empire''' ({{lang-ar|\u0627\u0644\u0625\u0645\u0628\u0631\u0627\u0637\u0648\u0631\u064a\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0645\u0627\u0646\u064a\u0629}}) was a powerful maritime empire, vying with [[Portugal]] and [[United Kingdom|Britain]] for influence in the [[Persian Gulf]] and [[Indian Ocean]]. At its peak in the 19th century, Omani influence or control extended across the [[Strait of Hormuz]] to modern-day [[Iran]] and [[Pakistan]], and as far south as [[Cape Delgado]]. After the death of [[Said bin Sultan, Sultan of Muscat and Oman|Said bin Sultan]] in 1856 the empire was divided into two sultanates, an African section ([[Sultanate of Zanzibar]]) ruled by [[Majid bin Said of Zanzibar|Majid bin Said]] and an Asian section ([[Muscat and Oman|Sultanate of Muscat and Oman]]) ruled by [[Thuwaini bin Said, Sultan of Muscat and Oman|Thuwaini bin Said]].\n\n== Becoming a regional power ==\nMuscat which was located in a strategic location on trade routes finally came under the control of the [[Portugal|Portuguese]] Empire between 1507 and 1650. However, the Portuguese didn't succeed in controlling Oman in its entirety. In mid-17th century, the Omani tribes were able to end the Portuguese presence in [[Muscat]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rafmuseum.org.uk/research/online-exhibitions/an-enduring-relationship-a-history-of-frienship-between-the-royal-air-force-and-the-royal-air-force-of-oman/a-history-of-oman.aspx|title=A History of Oman|website=www.rafmuseum.org.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-08-09}}</ref>\n\nIn the year 1696, under the reign of [[Saif bin Sultan]], an Omani fleet attacked [[Mombasa]], besieging the Portuguese [[Fort Jesus]], in which 2,500 of the population had taken refuge. The siege of the fort ended after 33 months when the garrison dying of hunger surrendered to the Omanis.{{Sfn|Beck|2004|p=}} In the following years, [[Saif bin Sultan]] continued a process of expansion down the east coast of Africa.<ref name=\":0\"/> By 1783, the Omani Empire had expanded eastwards to [[Gwadar]] in present day [[Pakistan]].<ref name=\":0\" /> The Omanis also continued attacking Portuguese bases in western [[India]].{{Sfn|Davies|1997|p=51-52}} In the north, the Omanis moved into the [[Persian Gulf]], taking [[Bahrain]] from the [[Persian people|Persians]], holding it for several years.{{Sfn|Davies|1997|p=52}} The expansion of Omani power and influence southwards included the first large-scale settlement of [[Zanzibar]] by Omani migrants.{{Sfn|Limbert|2010|p=153}}\n\n== Yaruba Dynasty ==\n{{Main|Saif bin Sultan}}The agriculture in Oman had undergone a massive improvement under Saif bin Sultan. He is known for providing water to the interior lands of Oman, while he encouraged Omani Arabs to move from the interior and settle along the coast by planting date palms in the coastal [[Al Batinah Region]].{{Sfn|Thomas|2011|p=222}} The town in the interior of Oman, [[Al Hamra, Oman|Al Hamra]], has it Irrigation system improved by the new built large [[Aflaj Irrigation Systems of Oman|falaj]], it seems that the [[Yaruba dynasty]] supported major investment in settlement and agricultural works such as terracing along the Wadi Bani Awf.{{Sfn|Siebert|2005|p=175}} Saif bin Sultan built new schools.{{Sfn|Plekhanov|2004|p=49}} He made the castle of [[Rustaq]] his residence, adding the Burj al Riah wind tower.{{Sfn|Ochs|1999|p=258}}\n\nSaif bin Sultan died on 4 October 1711. He was buried in the castle of Rustaq in a luxurious tomb, later destroyed by a [[Wahhabism|Wahhabi]] general.{{Sfn|Miles|1919|p=225}}  At his death he had great wealth, said to include 28 ships, 700 male slaves and one third of Oman's date trees. He was succeeded by his son.{{Sfn|Thomas|2011|p=222}} [[Sultan bin Saif II]] (r. 1711\u20131718) established his capital at Al-Hazm on the road from Rustaq to the coast. Now just a village, there still are remains of a great fortress that he built around 1710, and which contains his tomb.{{Sfn|JPM Guides|2000|p=85}}\n\n== Alliance with the British Empire ==\n[[Sultan bin Ahmad]] assumed control of the government after the death of his nephew and strengthened the already powerful fleet by adding numerous gunships and sleek cargo vessels, he also needed a strong ally to help him regain control of [[Mombasa]] from the [[Mazrui|Mazrui clan]], fight off the movement spreading from what is now [[Saudi Arabia]] and to keep the Qasimi tribes from the Persian city of  [[Bandar Lengeh|Lengeh]] out of [[Oman]]. He found this able ally in [[Great Britain]], who by this time was a powerful maritime nation with an [[British Empire|Empire]] expanding all over the world. In the late 18th century, the second [[British Empire]] was at war with [[France]] and knew that the French emperor, [[Napoleon|Napoleon Bonaparte]], was planning to march through [[Persia]] and capture [[Muscat]] on his way to invade [[India]]. In 1798 [[United Kingdom|Britain]] and [[Oman]] agreed a Treaty of Commerce and Navigation.\n\n[[Sultan bin Ahmad]] pledged himself to British interests in India, and his territories became out of bounds to the French. He allowed the [[East India Company|British East India Company]] to establish the first trading station in the Persian Gulf, and a British consul was posted to Muscat. As well as defeating Bonaparte, the British had another motive for the treaty with Oman: they wanted to put pressure on the sultan to end slavery, which had been declared illegal in England in 1772. At this time, the trade from Africa to Oman was still buoyant, and Zanzibar's position as an important trade centre was bolstered further when the supply of ivory from [[Mozambique]] to India collapsed because of excessive Portuguese export duties. The traders simply shipped their ivory through Zanzibar instead. Omani warships were in constant skirmishes up and down the gulf, which kept Sultan preoccupied. It was in the course of one of his sorties during an incursion abroad a ship in the Persian Gulf in 1804 that Sayyid Sultan was shot in the head by a stray bullet, he was buried in [[Bandar Lengeh|Lengeh]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britishempire.co.uk/maproom/oman/sultanate.htm|title=The British Empire, Imperialism, Colonialism, Colonies|website=www.britishempire.co.uk|access-date=2018-08-06}}</ref>\n\n== Relations with the United States of America ==\n{{refimprove section|date=May 2019}}\nOn 21 September 1833 a historic treaty of friendship and trade was signed with the [[United States|United States of America]]. It was the second trade treaty formulated by the U.S. and an Arab state ([[Morocco]] being the first in 1820). [[United States|The United States]] and [[Oman]] both stood to benefit, as the U.S. \u2013 unlike Britain and France \u2013 had no territorial ambitions in the [[Middle East]] and was solely interested in commerce. On 13 April 1840, the ship ''Al-Sultanah'' docked at [[New York City|New York]], making it the first Arab envoy to ever visit the New World. Her crew of fifty-six Arab sailors caused a flurry of excitement among the three hundred thousand residents of that thriving metropolis. ''Al-Sultanah'' carried ivory, Persian rugs, spices, coffee and dates, as well as lavish gifts for President [[Martin Van Buren]]. The visit of Al-Sultanah lasted nearly four months, in which time the emissary, [[Ahmad bin Na'aman Al Kaabi]], the first [[Arab]] emissary to visit the [[United States]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://epress.lib.uts.edu.au/journals/index.php/TfC/article/viewFile/1383/1447|title=MIRRORING MODERNITY: on consumerism in cosmopolitan Zanzibar|website=epress.lib.uts.edu.au}}</ref> (whose portrait can still be seen in the Oman and Zanzibar display of the Peabody Museum in [[Massachusetts]]) and his officers were entertained by state and city dignitaries. They received resolutions passed by official bodies, were given tours of New York City and saw sections which would, a few decades later, become colonies of Arabic-speaking immigrants. Among Bin Na'aman's hosts was Commodore [[Cornelius Vanderbilt]], in whose home he met Governor [[William H. Seward]] and Vice President [[Richard Mentor Johnson]]. The visit of [[Ahmad bin Na'aman Al Kaabi]] to America was a happy one, and when he prepared to leave, the United States completely repaired ''Al-Sultanah'' and presented him with gifts for his Sultan.\n\n== Said bin Sultan of Al Busaid Dynasty ==\n{{Main|Said bin Sultan, Sultan of Muscat and Oman|l1=Said bin Sultan}}[[Said bin Sultan, Sultan of Muscat and Oman|Said bin Sultan]] was son of [[Sultan bin Ahmad]], who ruled Oman from 1792 to 1804. Sultan bin Ahmad died in 1804 on an expedition to [[Basra]]. He appointed Mohammed bin Nasir bin Mohammed al-Jabry as the Regent and guardian of his two sons, [[Salim bin Sultan]] and Said bin Sultan.{{Sfn|Miles|1919|p=304}} Sultan's brother [[Qais bin Ahmad]], ruler of [[Sohar]], decided to attempt to seize power. Early in 1805 Qais and his brother Mohammed marched south along the coast to [[Muttrah]], which he easily captured. Qais then started to besiege Muscat. Mohammed bin Nasir tried to bribe Qais to leave, but did not succeed.{{Sfn|Miles|1919|p=304}}\n\nMohammed bin Nasir called on [[Badr bin Saif]] for help.{{Sfn|Miles|1919|p=304}} After a series of engagements, Qais was forced to retire to Sohar. Badr bin Saif became the effective ruler.{{Sfn|Miles|1919|p=305}} Allied with the Wahhabis, Badr bin Saif became increasingly unpopular.{{Sfn|Miles|1919|p=307}}To get his wards out of the way, Badr bin Saif made Salim bin Sultan governor of Al Ma\u015fna\u2018ah, on the Batinah coast and Said bin Sultan governor of [[Barka, Oman|Barka]].{{Sfn|Miles|1919|p=308}}\n\nIn 1806, Said bin Sultan lured Badr bin Saif to Barka and murdered him nearby. Said was proclaimed ruler of Oman. {{Sfn|Miles|1919|p=309}}There are different accounts of what happened, but it seems clear that Said struck the first blow and his supporters finished the job. Said was acclaimed by the people as a liberator from the Wahhabis, who left the country. Qais bin Ahmad at once gave his support to Said. Nervous of the Wahhabi reaction, Said blamed Mohammed bin Nasir for the murder.{{Sfn|Miles|1919|p=309}}\n\n== The division of the empire ==\nSchisms within the ruling family were apparent after the death of [[Said bin Sultan, Sultan of Muscat and Oman|Said bin Sultan]], as his sons who had their own rivalries and ambitions for controlling the throne quarreled over the empire. Realizing that [[Majid bin Said of Zanzibar|Majid]] would be unaware of their father\u2019s death, [[Barghash bin Said of Zanzibar|Barghash]] came ashore secretly and tried to take control of the palace at Mtoni and the fort in Zanzibar town, but he was unable to muster enough supporters and his attempt was thwarted.\n\nOn 28 October 1856, Majid proclaimed himself Sultan of Zanzibar. A ship was sent to Oman with the news, but Said's elder son [[Thuwaini bin Said, Sultan of Muscat and Oman|Thuwaini]], who was appointed heir apparent on 23 July 1844 and had long acted as his father's Governor in [[Muscat]] and commander-in-chief of the Saidi forces, refused to acknowledge Majid and immediately tried to regain [[Zanzibar]] by force of arms. As a direct result of this struggle, the government of British India, concerned with the stability in the area, acted as arbitrator in the dispute. The Governor-General of British India, [[Lord Canning]] ruled in his arbitration that the empire was to be divided into two separate sultanates: [[Sultanate of Zanzibar|The Sultanate of Zanzibar]] with its dependencies to [[Majid bin Said of Zanzibar|Majid bin Said]], Said's former Governor of the East African dominions, and [[Muscat and Oman|the Sultanate of Muscat and Oman]] to [[Thuwaini bin Said, Sultan of Muscat and Oman|Thuwaini bin Said]]. On 10 March 1862, the Zanzibar Guarantee Treaty was signed in [[Paris]] by [[United Kingdom|Britain]] and [[France]], whereby both parties agreed to respect the independence of the Sultan of Oman and the Sultan of Zanzibar. Recognizing the economic loss caused to Oman by the severance of the Zanzibar connection, Thuwaini insisted Majid pay 40,000 [[Maria Theresa thaler]]s annually as compensation but the payment fell into arrears and ceased a year later.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qKAtjJoXXpwC&pg=PA224 |title=The Rough Guide to Oman|last=|first=|publisher=Gavin Thomas|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=226}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== Sources ==\n{{portal|Oman}}\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv|url=http://www.san.beck.org/1-13-Africa1500-1800.html |accessdate=2013-11-11\n |last=Beck |first=Sanderson|year=2004|chapter=East Africa, Portuguese, and Arabs|title=Middle East & Africa to 1875}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv\n |last=Davies|first=Charles E.|title=The Blood-red Arab Flag: An Investigation Into Qasimi Piracy, 1797-1820\n |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tGboFK2QPUwC&pg=PA52|accessdate=2013-11-11\n |date=1997-01-01|publisher=University of Exeter Press|isbn=978-0-85989-509-5}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv\n |last=Limbert|first=Mandana|title=In the Time of Oil: Piety, Memory, and Social Life in an Omani Town\n |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zs3FT5SZ_2cC&pg=PT153|accessdate=2013-11-11\n |date=2010-06-07|publisher=Stanford University Press|isbn=978-0-8047-7460-4}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv\n |last=Thomas|first=Gavin|title=The Rough Guide to Oman|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qKAtjJoXXpwC&pg=PA222|accessdate=2013-11-11\n |date=2011-11-01|publisher=Penguin|isbn=978-1-4053-8935-8}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv\n |last=Siebert|first=Stefan|title=Analysis of Arid Agricultural Systems Using Quantitative Image Analysis, Modeling and Geographical Information Systems\n |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rTjTRBsw_BgC&pg=PA175|accessdate=2013-11-11\n |year=2005|publisher=kassel university press GmbH|isbn=978-3-89958-192-8}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv\n |last=Ochs|first=Peter J.|title=Maverick Guide to Oman|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WTP47KlX4hUC&pg=PA258|accessdate=2013-11-11\n |date=1999-11-01|publisher=Pelican Publishing|isbn=978-1-4556-0865-2}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv\n |last=Plekhanov|first=Sergey|title=A Reformer on the Throne: Sultan Qaboos Bin Said Al Said\n |url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_-U8BL-tEPLwC|page=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_-U8BL-tEPLwC/page/n51 49]\n |accessdate=2013-11-11\n |year=2004|publisher=Trident Press Ltd|isbn=978-1-900724-70-8}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv\n |last=Miles|first=Samuel Barrett|authorlink=Samuel Barrett Miles|title=The Countries and Tribes of the Persian Gulf|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dbsOoPpZiSEC&pg=PA225|accessdate=2013-11-11\n |year=1919|publisher=Garnet & Ithaca Press|isbn=978-1-873938-56-0}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv\n |author=JPM Guides|title=Gulf States|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=K8nMCRYnKn8C&pg=PA85|accessdate=2013-11-11\n |date=2000-03-01|publisher=Hunter Publishing, Inc|isbn=978-2-88452-099-7}}\n\n[[Category:Former sultanates]]\n[[Category:Former countries in the Middle East]]\n\n{{improve categories|date=December 2018}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox former country|capital=[[Rustaq]]<br />{{small|(1692\u20131792)}}<br>[[Muscat]]<br />{{small|(1792\u20131840)}}<br>[[Zanzibar]]<br />{{small|(1840\u20131856)}}|common_languages='''Official:''' [[Arabic language|Arabic]]<br/>'''Regional:''' <br/>[[Persian language|Persian]]<br/>[[English language|English]]<br/>[[Swahili language|Swahili]]<br/>[[Omani Arabic]]<br/>[[Yemeni Arabic]]<br/>[[Balochi language|Balochi]]<br/>[[Somali language|Somali]]|common_name=Omani Empire|conventional_long_name=Omani Empire|currency=[[Dirham]]<br/>[[Indian rupee]]<br/>[[Maria Theresa thaler]]<br/>[[Shilling]]|date_event1=1718|event_start=Maritime Empire started by<br />[[Saif bin Sultan]]|event_end=Divided into<br />two Sultanates<br />|event1=Civil War<br />commenced|event2=Persian invasion<br />of [[Sohar]]|date_event2=1742|event3=[[House of Al Said|Al Busaid Dynasty]]<br /> took over|date_event3=1749|event4=Treaty with the<br />United States|date_event4=1837|deputy1=[[Ahmad bin Said al-Busaidi|Ahmad bin Said]]|deputy2=[[Said bin Ahmed]]|deputy3=Hamad bin Said|deputy4=Sultan bin Ahmed|deputy5=Badr bin Seif|deputy6=[[Said bin Sultan, Sultan of Muscat and Oman|Said bin Sultan]] {{small|(last)}}|flag_s1=Flag of Muscat.svg|flag_type=|image_flag=Om_1958.gif|image_coat=National emblem of Oman.svg|image_flag2=Flag of Muscat.svg|image_map=Empire of Oman.svg|image_map_caption={{small|'''Omani Empire at its peak under Said bin Sultan.'''}}\n<div style=\"text-align:left;\">|government_type={{nowrap|[[Monarchy]]}}|leader1=[[Saif bin Sultan]] {{small|(first)}}|leader2=[[Sultan bin Saif II]]|leader3=[[Saif bin Sultan II]]|leader4=[[Muhanna bin Sultan]]|leader5=[[Ya'arab bin Bel'arab]]|leader6=[[Muhammad bin Nasir]]|leader7=[[Sultan bin Murshid]]|leader8=[[Bal'arab bin Himyar]]|native_name=\u0627\u0644\u0625\u0645\u0628\u0631\u0627\u0637\u0648\u0631\u064a\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0645\u0627\u0646\u064a\u0629|p1=Imamate of Oman|religion='''Dominant:'''<br/>[[Ibadi Islam]]<br/>'''Minor:'''<br/>[[Shia Islam]]<br/>[[Sunni Islam]]<br/>[[Christianity]]<br/>[[Hindu]]|s1=Muscat and Oman|s2=Sultanate of Zanzibar|s3=|s4=|year_start=1696|year_end=1856|year_leader1=1692\u20131711|year_leader2=1711\u20131718|year_leader3=1718\u20131719|year_leader4=1719\u20131720|year_leader5=1722\u20131723|year_leader6=1724\u20131728|year_leader7=1742\u20131743|year_leader8=1743\u20131749|year_deputy1=1744\u20131778|year_deputy2=1778\u20131783|year_deputy3=1783\u20131793|year_deputy4=1792\u20131804|year_deputy5=1805\u20131806|year_deputy6=1806\u20131856|status=Empire|flag_p1=Flag of The Imamate of Oman.svg|flag_s2=Flag of the Sultanate of Zanzibar (1963).svg|title_deputy=[[House of Al Said|Al Busaid Dynasty]]|title_leader=[[Yaruba dynasty|Yaruba Dynasty]]|stat_area1=1407118|stat_year1=1840 est.}}\n'''The Omani Empire''' ([[Arabic]]: \u0627\u0644\u0625\u0645\u0628\u0631\u0627\u0637\u0648\u0631\u064a\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0645\u0627\u0646\u064a\u0629) was a powerful maritime empire, vying with [[Portugal]] and [[United Kingdom|Britain]] for influence in the [[Persian Gulf]] and [[Indian Ocean]]. At its peak in the 19th century, Omani influence or control extended across the [[Strait of Hormuz]] to modern-day [[Iran]] and [[Pakistan]], and as far south as [[Cape Delgado]]. After the death of [[Said bin Sultan, Sultan of Muscat and Oman|Said bin Sultan]] in 1856 the empire was divided into two sultanates, an African section ([[Sultanate of Zanzibar]]) ruled by [[Majid bin Said of Zanzibar|Majid bin Said]] and an Asian section ([[Muscat and Oman|Sultanate of Muscat and Oman]]) ruled by [[Thuwaini bin Said, Sultan of Muscat and Oman|Thuwaini bin Said]].\n\n== Becoming a regional power ==\nMuscat which was located in a strategic location on trade routes finally came under the control of the [[Portugal|Portuguese]] Empire between 1507 and 1650. However, the Portuguese didn't succeed in controlling Oman in its entirety. In mid-17th century, the Omani tribes were able to end the Portuguese presence in [[Muscat]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rafmuseum.org.uk/research/online-exhibitions/an-enduring-relationship-a-history-of-frienship-between-the-royal-air-force-and-the-royal-air-force-of-oman/a-history-of-oman.aspx|title=A History of Oman|website=www.rafmuseum.org.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-08-09}}</ref>\n\nIn the year 1696, under the reign of [[Saif bin Sultan]], an Omani fleet attacked [[Mombasa]], besieging the Portuguese [[Fort Jesus]], in which 2,500 of the population had taken refuge. The siege of the fort ended after 33 months when the garrison dying of hunger surrendered to the Omanis.{{Sfn|Beck|2004|p=}} In the following years, [[Saif bin Sultan]] continued a process of expansion down the east coast of Africa.<ref name=\":0\"/> By 1783, the Omani Empire had expanded eastwards to [[Gwadar]] in present day [[Pakistan]].<ref name=\":0\" /> The Omanis also continued attacking Portuguese bases in western [[India]].{{Sfn|Davies|1997|p=51-52}} In the north, the Omanis moved into the [[Persian Gulf]], taking [[Bahrain]] from the [[Persian people|Persians]], holding it for several years.{{Sfn|Davies|1997|p=52}} The expansion of Omani power and influence southwards included the first large-scale settlement of [[Zanzibar]] by Omani migrants.{{Sfn|Limbert|2010|p=153}}\n\n== Yaruba Dynasty ==\n{{Main|Saif bin Sultan}}The agriculture in Oman had undergone a massive improvement under Saif bin Sultan. He is known for providing water to the interior lands of Oman, while he encouraged Omani Arabs to move from the interior and settle along the coast by planting date palms in the coastal [[Al Batinah Region]].{{Sfn|Thomas|2011|p=222}} The town in the interior of Oman, [[Al Hamra, Oman|Al Hamra]], has it Irrigation system improved by the new built large [[Aflaj Irrigation Systems of Oman|falaj]], it seems that the [[Yaruba dynasty]] supported major investment in settlement and agricultural works such as terracing along the Wadi Bani Awf.{{Sfn|Siebert|2005|p=175}} Saif bin Sultan built new schools.{{Sfn|Plekhanov|2004|p=49}} He made the castle of [[Rustaq]] his residence, adding the Burj al Riah wind tower.{{Sfn|Ochs|1999|p=258}}\n\nSaif bin Sultan died on 4 October 1711. He was buried in the castle of Rustaq in a luxurious tomb, later destroyed by a [[Wahhabism|Wahhabi]] general.{{Sfn|Miles|1919|p=225}}  At his death he had great wealth, said to include 28 ships, 700 male slaves and one third of Oman's date trees. He was succeeded by his son.{{Sfn|Thomas|2011|p=222}} [[Sultan bin Saif II]] (r. 1711\u20131718) established his capital at Al-Hazm on the road from Rustaq to the coast. Now just a village, there still are remains of a great fortress that he built around 1710, and which contains his tomb.{{Sfn|JPM Guides|2000|p=85}}\n\n== Alliance with the British Empire ==\n[[Sultan bin Ahmad]] assumed control of the government after the death of his nephew and strengthened the already powerful fleet by adding numerous gunships and sleek cargo vessels, he also needed a strong ally to help him regain control of [[Mombasa]] from the [[Mazrui|Mazrui clan]], fight off the movement spreading from what is now [[Saudi Arabia]] and to keep the Qasimi tribes from the Persian city of  [[Bandar Lengeh|Lengeh]] out of [[Oman]]. He found this able ally in [[Great Britain]], who by this time was a powerful maritime nation with an [[British Empire|Empire]] expanding all over the world. In the late 18th century, the second [[British Empire]] was at war with [[France]] and knew that the French emperor, [[Napoleon|Napoleon Bonaparte]], was planning to march through [[Persia]] and capture [[Muscat]] on his way to invade [[India]]. In 1798 [[United Kingdom|Britain]] and [[Oman]] agreed a Treaty of Commerce and Navigation.\n\n[[Sultan bin Ahmad]] pledged himself to British interests in India, and his territories became out of bounds to the French. He allowed the [[East India Company|British East India Company]] to establish the first trading station in the Persian Gulf, and a British consul was posted to Muscat. As well as defeating Bonaparte, the British had another motive for the treaty with Oman: they wanted to put pressure on the sultan to end slavery, which had been declared illegal in England in 1772. At this time, the trade from Africa to Oman was still buoyant, and Zanzibar's position as an important trade centre was bolstered further when the supply of ivory from [[Mozambique]] to India collapsed because of excessive Portuguese export duties. The traders simply shipped their ivory through Zanzibar instead. Omani warships were in constant skirmishes up and down the gulf, which kept Sultan preoccupied. It was in the course of one of his sorties during an incursion abroad a ship in the Persian Gulf in 1804 that Sayyid Sultan was shot in the head by a stray bullet, he was buried in [[Bandar Lengeh|Lengeh]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britishempire.co.uk/maproom/oman/sultanate.htm|title=The British Empire, Imperialism, Colonialism, Colonies|website=www.britishempire.co.uk|access-date=2018-08-06}}</ref>\n\n== Relations with the United States of America ==\n{{refimprove section|date=May 2019}}\nOn 21 September 1833 a historic treaty of friendship and trade was signed with the [[United States|United States of America]]. It was the second trade treaty formulated by the U.S. and an Arab state ([[Morocco]] being the first in 1820). [[United States|The United States]] and [[Oman]] both stood to benefit, as the U.S. \u2013 unlike Britain and France \u2013 had no territorial ambitions in the [[Middle East]] and was solely interested in commerce. On 13 April 1840, the ship ''Al-Sultanah'' docked at [[New York City|New York]], making it the first Arab envoy to ever visit the New World. Her crew of fifty-six Arab sailors caused a flurry of excitement among the three hundred thousand residents of that thriving metropolis. ''Al-Sultanah'' carried ivory, Persian rugs, spices, coffee and dates, as well as lavish gifts for President [[Martin Van Buren]]. The visit of Al-Sultanah lasted nearly four months, in which time the emissary, [[Ahmad bin Na'aman Al Kaabi]], the first [[Arab]] emissary to visit the [[United States]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://epress.lib.uts.edu.au/journals/index.php/TfC/article/viewFile/1383/1447|title=MIRRORING MODERNITY: on consumerism in cosmopolitan Zanzibar|website=epress.lib.uts.edu.au}}</ref> (whose portrait can still be seen in the Oman and Zanzibar display of the Peabody Museum in [[Massachusetts]]) and his officers were entertained by state and city dignitaries. They received resolutions passed by official bodies, were given tours of New York City and saw sections which would, a few decades later, become colonies of Arabic-speaking immigrants. Among Bin Na'aman's hosts was Commodore [[Cornelius Vanderbilt]], in whose home he met Governor [[William H. Seward]] and Vice President [[Richard Mentor Johnson]]. The visit of [[Ahmad bin Na'aman Al Kaabi]] to America was a happy one, and when he prepared to leave, the United States completely repaired ''Al-Sultanah'' and presented him with gifts for his Sultan.\n\n== Said bin Sultan of Al Busaid Dynasty ==\n{{Main|Said bin Sultan, Sultan of Muscat and Oman|l1=Said bin Sultan}}[[Said bin Sultan, Sultan of Muscat and Oman|Said bin Sultan]] was son of [[Sultan bin Ahmad]], who ruled Oman from 1792 to 1804. Sultan bin Ahmad died in 1804 on an expedition to [[Basra]]. He appointed Mohammed bin Nasir bin Mohammed al-Jabry as the Regent and guardian of his two sons, [[Salim bin Sultan]] and Said bin Sultan.{{Sfn|Miles|1919|p=304}} Sultan's brother [[Qais bin Ahmad]], ruler of [[Sohar]], decided to attempt to seize power. Early in 1805 Qais and his brother Mohammed marched south along the coast to [[Muttrah]], which he easily captured. Qais then started to besiege Muscat. Mohammed bin Nasir tried to bribe Qais to leave, but did not succeed.{{Sfn|Miles|1919|p=304}}\n\nMohammed bin Nasir called on [[Badr bin Saif]] for help.{{Sfn|Miles|1919|p=304}} After a series of engagements, Qais was forced to retire to Sohar. Badr bin Saif became the effective ruler.{{Sfn|Miles|1919|p=305}} Allied with the Wahhabis, Badr bin Saif became increasingly unpopular.{{Sfn|Miles|1919|p=307}}To get his wards out of the way, Badr bin Saif made Salim bin Sultan governor of Al Ma\u015fna\u2018ah, on the Batinah coast and Said bin Sultan governor of [[Barka, Oman|Barka]].{{Sfn|Miles|1919|p=308}}\n\nIn 1806, Said bin Sultan lured Badr bin Saif to Barka and murdered him nearby. Said was proclaimed ruler of Oman. {{Sfn|Miles|1919|p=309}}There are different accounts of what happened, but it seems clear that Said struck the first blow and his supporters finished the job. Said was acclaimed by the people as a liberator from the Wahhabis, who left the country. Qais bin Ahmad at once gave his support to Said. Nervous of the Wahhabi reaction, Said blamed Mohammed bin Nasir for the murder.{{Sfn|Miles|1919|p=309}}\n\n== The division of the empire ==\nSchisms within the ruling family were apparent after the death of [[Said bin Sultan, Sultan of Muscat and Oman|Said bin Sultan]], as his sons who had their own rivalries and ambitions for controlling the throne quarreled over the empire. Realizing that [[Majid bin Said of Zanzibar|Majid]] would be unaware of their father\u2019s death, [[Barghash bin Said of Zanzibar|Barghash]] came ashore secretly and tried to take control of the palace at Mtoni and the fort in Zanzibar town, but he was unable to muster enough supporters and his attempt was thwarted.\n\nOn 28 October 1856, Majid proclaimed himself Sultan of Zanzibar. A ship was sent to Oman with the news, but Said's elder son [[Thuwaini bin Said, Sultan of Muscat and Oman|Thuwaini]], who was appointed heir apparent on 23 July 1844 and had long acted as his father's Governor in [[Muscat]] and commander-in-chief of the Saidi forces, refused to acknowledge Majid and immediately tried to regain [[Zanzibar]] by force of arms. As a direct result of this struggle, the government of British India, concerned with the stability in the area, acted as arbitrator in the dispute. The Governor-General of British India, [[Lord Canning]] ruled in his arbitration that the empire was to be divided into two separate sultanates: [[Sultanate of Zanzibar|The Sultanate of Zanzibar]] with its dependencies to [[Majid bin Said of Zanzibar|Majid bin Said]], Said's former Governor of the East African dominions, and [[Muscat and Oman|the Sultanate of Muscat and Oman]] to [[Thuwaini bin Said, Sultan of Muscat and Oman|Thuwaini bin Said]]. On 10 March 1862, the Zanzibar Guarantee Treaty was signed in [[Paris]] by [[United Kingdom|Britain]] and [[France]], whereby both parties agreed to respect the independence of the Sultan of Oman and the Sultan of Zanzibar. Recognizing the economic loss caused to Oman by the severance of the Zanzibar connection, Thuwaini insisted Majid pay 40,000 [[Maria Theresa thaler]]s annually as compensation but the payment fell into arrears and ceased a year later.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qKAtjJoXXpwC&pg=PA224 |title=The Rough Guide to Oman|last=|first=|publisher=Gavin Thomas|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=226}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== Sources ==\n{{portal|Oman}}\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv|url=http://www.san.beck.org/1-13-Africa1500-1800.html |accessdate=2013-11-11\n |last=Beck |first=Sanderson|year=2004|chapter=East Africa, Portuguese, and Arabs|title=Middle East & Africa to 1875}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv\n |last=Davies|first=Charles E.|title=The Blood-red Arab Flag: An Investigation Into Qasimi Piracy, 1797-1820\n |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tGboFK2QPUwC&pg=PA52|accessdate=2013-11-11\n |date=1997-01-01|publisher=University of Exeter Press|isbn=978-0-85989-509-5}}\n*{